<#tt0119349-Aldanoli>
	schema:about <#tt0119349>;
	schema:author "Aldanoli";
	schema:dateCreated "Sat Sep 04 1999 00:00:00 GMT+0200 (Mitteleuropäische Sommerzeit)";
	schema:reviewRating 1;
	schema:headline " An unimaginable waste of time";
	schema:reviewBody "What is most distressing at the end of this movie is that two hours of your life that you will never get back have been stolen from youand that they were spent with the most repellent characters this side of a Peter Greenaway movie. It is hard to say what is more unbelievablethat people in the 1970s supposedly acted like this or that we are supposed to accept the moviemaker's notion that people acted like this.What exactly is the point to all this? That people who live in funnyshaped houses are themselves warped? That we should all be thankful that we did not live in Connecticut in the early 1970s? That it's not a good idea to play outside during an ice storm?There isn't a single character here for the audience to sympathize with Joan Allen's character comes off best although she's basically a victim and Tobey Maguire's character as her son comes in second because he doesn't do what any other male character in the movie presumably would have donetake advantage of the young woman who passes out in his arms. But it's hard to see why anyone would make a movie about the rest of this sleazy pack who swing like a pendulum between the immoral and the clueless.It's too bad really because there are one or two moments where some real emotion claws through the patentlyfalse exteriors that we are supposed to believe in Kevin Kline picking up his daughter and carrying her home through a gathering snowstorm for example. At least some of it could have rung truethe voiceover commentary by Maguire's character for example which makes an analogy between the comic book he's reading and his family or the happy ending at the train station by our nowchastened and supposedly nowenlightened family. But that would have required that the rest of the story be about real people not cardboard characters. As projected on this bunch of imbeciles the whole exercise is simply a waste of the viewer's time and a waste of a capable cast.".

<#tt0119349-Aldanoli-random>
	rdf:type onyx:EmotionSet;
	onyx:emotionText "What is most distressing at the end of this movie is that two hours of your life that you will never get back have been stolen from youand that they were spent with the most repellent characters this side of a Peter Greenaway movie. It is hard to say what is more unbelievablethat people in the 1970s supposedly acted like this or that we are supposed to accept the moviemaker's notion that people acted like this.What exactly is the point to all this? That people who live in funnyshaped houses are themselves warped? That we should all be thankful that we did not live in Connecticut in the early 1970s? That it's not a good idea to play outside during an ice storm?There isn't a single character here for the audience to sympathize with Joan Allen's character comes off best although she's basically a victim and Tobey Maguire's character as her son comes in second because he doesn't do what any other male character in the movie presumably would have donetake advantage of the young woman who passes out in his arms. But it's hard to see why anyone would make a movie about the rest of this sleazy pack who swing like a pendulum between the immoral and the clueless.It's too bad really because there are one or two moments where some real emotion claws through the patentlyfalse exteriors that we are supposed to believe in Kevin Kline picking up his daughter and carrying her home through a gathering snowstorm for example. At least some of it could have rung truethe voiceover commentary by Maguire's character for example which makes an analogy between the comic book he's reading and his family or the happy ending at the train station by our nowchastened and supposedly nowenlightened family. But that would have required that the rest of the story be about real people not cardboard characters. As projected on this bunch of imbeciles the whole exercise is simply a waste of the viewer's time and a waste of a capable cast.";
	onyx:describesObject <#tt0119349>;
	onyx:hasEmotion <#Apathy>;
	prov:Entity <#tt0119349-Aldanoli>.

